DON TOMMASSINO You must go right away.
MICHAEL What is it?
DON TOMMASSINO Bad news from America.
DON TOMMASSINO Your brother, Santino.
DON TOMMASSINO He has been killed.
For a moment, the whole world of New York, Sollozzo, the Five Family War, all comes back to MICHAEL.
Morning.
MICHAEL leans out of the bedroom window.
Below, FABRIZZIO is sitting in one of the garden chairs, combing his thick hair.
MICHAEL whistles and FABRIZZIO looks up to his window.
MICHAEL Get the car.
MICHAEL I'll be leaving in ten minutes.
MICHAEL Where's Calo?
FABRIZZIO Calo is having a cup of coffee in the kitchen.
FABRIZZIO Is your wife coming with you?
MICHAEL No, she's going home to her family.
MICHAEL She'll join me in a few weeks...
MICHAEL, dressed, crosses from the hallway, and into the kitchen.
CALO is just finishing a bite.
He rises when he sees MICHAEL.
CALO Should I get your bag?
MICHAEL No, I'll get it.
MICHAEL Where's Appolonia?
CALO She is sitting in the driver's seat of the car, dying to step on the gas.
CALO She'll be a real American woman before she gets to America.
MICHAEL smiles.
MICHAEL Tell Fabrizzio and wait for me in the car.
He leaves the kitchen, after a quick sip of coffee.
He looks out from the opening in the doorway.
There is the car, with APPOLONIA sitting in the driver's seat, playing with the wheel like a child.
CALO moves to the car, and puts a lunch basket in the rear seat.
Then MICHAEL seems disturbed.
Over, on the other side of the courtyard, he sees FABRIZZIO disappear through the gate.
MICHAEL Where the hell is he going?
MICHAEL goes down the hallway, and outside.
MICHAEL steps out into the bright sunlight of the outer courtyard, causing him to shade his eyes.
APPOLONIA sees him, and waves, motioning that he should stay where he is.
APPOLONIA I'll drive to you.
He smiles affectionately.
CALO stands beside the car, smiling, with his lupara dangling by his side.
There is no sight of FABRIZZIO.
Suddenly the smile fades from MICHAEL's face.
He steps forward and holds out his hand.
MICHAEL No.
MICHAEL No!
His shout is drowned in the roar of a tremendous EXPLOSION, as she switched on the ignition.
Part of the wall is caved in, the kitchen door is blown off; and there is nothing left of the Alpha, or of Appolonia.
MICHAEL is thrown against the wall, and knocked unconscious.
MICHAEL is unconscious in a darkened room.
We hear whispering around him, but can't make any of it out.
A soft cloth is applied to his face; gradually his eyes open.
DON TOMMASSINO is there, close to him.
He looks at them and from their grave expressions, he knows his wife is dead.
MICHAEL Fabrizzio.
MICHAEL Let your shepherds know that the one who gives me Fabrizzio will own the finest pastures in Sicily.
Easter.
A HIGH VIEW ON THE CORLEONE MALL in the springtime.
Hordes of little CHILDREN including many of the Corleone Children and Grandchilren, rush about carrying little Easter baskets, searching here and there for candy treasures and hidden Easter eggs.
The DON himself, much older, much smaller in size, wearing baggy pants and a plaid shirt and an old hat, moves around his garden, tending rows and rows of rich tomato plants.
Suddenly, he stops and looks.
MICHAEL stands there, still holding his suitcase.
Great emotion comes over the DON, who takes a few steps in MICHAEL's direction.
MICHAEL leaves his suitcase and walks to his favorite son and embraces him.
DON CORLEONE Be my son...
DON CORLEONE leads MICHAEL through the corridors of the building.
DON CORLEONE This old building has seen its day.
DON CORLEONE No way to do business...too small, too old.
They enter the DON's glass-panelled office.
DON CORLEONE Have you thought about a wife?
DON CORLEONE A family?
MICHAEL No.
DON CORLEONE I understand, Michael.
DON CORLEONE But you must make a family, you know.
MICHAEL I want children, I want a family.
MICHAEL But I don't know when.
DON CORLEONE Accept what's happened, Michael.
MICHAEL I could accept everything that's happened; I could accept it, but that I never had a choice.
MICHAEL From the time I was born, you had laid this all out for me.
DON CORLEONE No, I wanted other things for you.
MICHAEL You wanted me to be your son.
DON CORLEONE Yes, but sons who would be professors, scientists, musicians...and grandchildren who could be, who knows, a Governor, a President even, nothing's impossible here in America.
MICHAEL Then why have I become a man like you?
DON CORLEONE You are like me, we refuse to be fools, to be puppets dancing on a string pulled by other men.
DON CORLEONE I hoped the time for guns and killing and massacres was over.
DON CORLEONE That was my misfortune.
DON CORLEONE That was your misfortune.
DON CORLEONE I was hunted on the streets of Corleone when I was twelve years old because of who my father was.
DON CORLEONE I had no choice.
MICHAEL A man has to choose what he will be.
MICHAEL I believe that.
DON CORLEONE What else do you believe in?
MICHAEL doesn't answer.
DON CORLEONE Believe in a family.
DON CORLEONE Can you believe in your country?
DON CORLEONE Those Pezzonovante of the State who decide what we shall do with our lives?
DON CORLEONE Who declare wars they wish us to fight in to protect what they own.
DON CORLEONE Do you put your fate in the hands of men whose only talent is that they tricked a bloc of people to vote for them?
DON CORLEONE Michael, in five years the Corleone family can be completely legitimate.
DON CORLEONE Very difficult things have to happen to make that possible.
DON CORLEONE I can't do them anymore, but you can, if you choose to.
MICHAEL listens.
DON CORLEONE Believe in a family; believe in a Code of Honor, older and higher, believe in Roots that go back thousands of years into your Race.
DON CORLEONE Make a family, Michael, and protect it.
DON CORLEONE These are our affairs, sono cosa nostra, Governments only protect men who have their own individual power.
DON CORLEONE Be one of those men...you have the choice.
A MOVING VIEW, driving up the Las Vegas Strip of 1955.
FREDO There's a new one.
FREDO Construction going on everywhere.
MORE VIEWS, showing new hotels and casinos being built; the bill marquees read: "MARTIN AND LEWIS", "PATTI PAGE", etc.
FREDO That's one of the family's new ones.
FREDO Not bad, eh?
The car pulls up at the Flamingo Hotel.
Inside the car: MICHAEL, FREDO, TOM HAGEN and a new man, NERI, quiet and sinister.
MICHAEL Why didn't Moe Green meet us at the airport?
FREDO He had business at the hotel, but he'll drop in for dinner.
From the expression on MICHAEL's face we know this is a discourtesy.
A whole entourage precedes FREDO and his V.I.P. party of MICHAEL, HAGEN and NERI.
Great fuss is made.
They are being shown into the hotel's 'special' suite.
FREDO You look wonderful, kid; really wonderful.
FREDO That doctor did some job on your face.
MICHAEL You look good, too.
They enter the suite.
FREDO Nice, eh?
FREDO is as excited as a kid, snapping orders at the bellboys, waiters and maids.
FREDO Kid, take a look-see.
MICHAEL gives a look to HAGEN, and continues into the bedroom.
There is an enormous circular bed on a huge platform, mirrors to each side.
FREDO points upward.
A VIEW into a large CEILING mirror.
FREDO Ever seen anything like that before?
MICHAEL No.
MICHAEL is alone in the bedroom.
He is just finishing dressing; he puts on his jacket.
From the window, with the lights blinking, we can tell it's late at night.
MICHAEL passes into the other room.
He stops, looks.
He is disturbed.
A magnificent, circular table has been set up in his suite; a lavish table setting for eight.
Standing by the table are HAGEN, JOHNNY FONTANE, looking wonderful, a little heavier, beautifully dressed; FREDO, a dandy, and TWO LAS VEGAS GIRLS.
NERI stands quietly by the door.
FREDO Mike!
FREDO The party starting!
MICHAEL Come here a minute, Fredo.
FREDO goes to him, a big smile all over his face.
MICHAEL Who are those girls?
FREDO That's for you to find out.
MICHAEL Give them some money and send them home.
FREDO Mike!
MICHAEL Get rid of them...
They are seated around the lavish table in Michael's suite.
MICHAEL is speaking to JOHNNY.
MICHAEL Johnny, the Corleone family is thinking of selling out all our interests in the Olive Oil business and settling here.
MICHAEL Moe Greene will sell us his interest so it can be wholly owned by friends of the family.
FREDDIE seems anxious.
FREDO Mike, you sure about Moe selling.
FREDO He never mentioned it to me and he loves the business.
MICHAEL I'll make him an offer he can't refuse.
MICHAEL turns to JOHNNY.
MICHAEL Johnny, the Don wants you to help us get started.
MICHAEL We figure entertainment will be the big factor in drawing gamblers.
MICHAEL We hope you'll sign a contract to appear five times a year for maybe a week long engagement.
MICHAEL We hope your friends in the movies will do the same.
MICHAEL We count on you to convince them.
JOHNNY Sure, I'll do anything for my Godfather.
JOHNNY You know that, Mike.
There is knock on the door.
NERI rises, looks at MICHAEL, who nods.
NERI opens the door, and MOE GREENE enters, followed by TWO BODYGUARDS.
He is a handsome hood, dressed in the Hollywood style.
His BODYGUARDS are more West Coast style.
MOE Mike, good to see you.
MOE Got everything you want?
MICHAEL Thanks.
MOE The chef cooked for you special; the dancers will kick your tongue out and you credit is good!
MOE Draw chips for all these people so they can play on the house.
MICHAEL Is my credit good enough to buy you out?
MOE laughs.
MOE Buy me out?...
MICHAEL The hotel, the casino.
MICHAEL The Corleone family wants to buy you out.
GREENE stops laughing; the room becomes tense.
NERI eyes the BODYGUARDS.
MOE The Corleone family wants to buy me out.
MOE I buy you out.
MOE You don't buy me out.
MICHAEL Your casino loses money.
MICHAEL Maybe we can do better.
MOE You think I scam?
MICHAEL You're unlucky.
MOE You goddamn dagos.
MOE I do you a favor and take Freddie in when you're having a bad time, and then you try to push me out.
