MICHAEL You and the Corleone family are evened out.
MICHAEL This is for business; name your price.
MOE The Corleone family don't have that kind of muscle anymore.
MOE The Godfather is sick.
MOE You're getting chased out of New York by Barzini and the other families, and you think you can find easier pickings here.
MOE I've talked to Barzini; I can make a deal with him and keep my hotel!
MICHAEL Is that why you thought you could slap Freddie around in public?
FREDO Ah Mike, that was nothing.
FREDO Moe didn't mean anything.
FREDO He flies off the handle sometimes; but me and him are good friends.
FREDO Right, Moe?
MOE Yeah sure.
MOE Sometimes I gotta kick asses to make this place run right.
MOE Freddie and I had a little argument and I had to straighten him out.
MICHAEL You straightened my brother out?
MOE Hell, he was banging cocktail waitresses two at a time.
MOE Players couldn't get a drink.
MICHAEL rises from his chair, and says in a tone of dismissal:
MICHAEL I have to go back to New York tomorrow.
MICHAEL Think of your price.
MOE You son of a bitch, you think you can brush me off like that?
MOE I made my bones when you were going out with cheerleaders.
FREDO Tom, you're the Consigliere; you can talk to the Don and advise him.
MICHAEL The Don has semi-retired.
MICHAEL I'm running the Family business now.
